n": "AhR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9977185726165771, "span": {"begin": 510, "end": 513}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "nuclear 6S form", "obj": "RNA", "prob": 0.6065048575401306, "span": {"begin": 526, "end": 541}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:405"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ARNT", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9936742782592773, "span": {"begin": 543, "end": 547}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "nuclear 6S form", "obj": "RNA", "prob": 0.5980046391487122, "span": {"begin": 560, "end": 575}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "6S form", "obj": "RNA", "prob": 0.49985456466674805, "span": {"begin": 594, "end": 601}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:196"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "AhR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9856734275817871, "span": {"begin": 605, "end": 608}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:196"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "AhR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9981529116630554, "span": {"begin": 643, "end": 646}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:405"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ARNT", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9950255751609802, "span": {"begin": 676, "end": 680}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:196"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AhRs", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9910479187965393, "span": {"begin": 766, "end": 770}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:405", "375056"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ARNTs", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9823853373527527, "span": {"begin": 776, "end": 781}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "response elements", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.8707818984985352, "span": {"begin": 983, "end": 1000}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:196"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "AhR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9980087876319885, "span": {"begin": 1039, "end": 1042}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:405"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ARNT", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9966004490852356, "span": {"begin": 1050, "end": 1054}}], "text": "ARNT is a necessary dimerization partner for the transcriptional activation of AHR regulated genes (Hoffman et al. 1991; Poland et al. 1976). The AHR/ARNT complex was confirmed following in vitro exposure to halogenated aromatic hydrocarbons using an electrophoretic mobility shift assay; a dose-dependent supershift in DNA-binding was observed using specific antibodies in chicken and human cell lines (Heid et al. 2001).    Unliganded AhR exists as a cytosolic 9S form, while in the presence of a ligand the AhR exists as a nuclear 6S form. ARNT exists as a nuclear 6S form (Okey 2007).  The 6S form of AhR is approximately 210 kDa. Ligated AhR is approximately 100 kDa and ARNT is approximately 110 kDa (Elferink et al 1990; Swanson et al 1993).  Dimerization of AhRs with ARNTs has been demonstrated in all invertebrate and vertebrate species so far investigated (Butler et al 2001; Emmons et al 1999; Hahn et al 2002; Powell-Coffman et al 1998).  Heterodimers are not formed on response elements in gel shift assays in the absence of AhR and/or ARNT (Tanguay et al 2000).&nbsp;   &nbsp;", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:33:36 +0000 2026"}